<DIV class=3Dpost-content>
<P>I couldn=E2=80=99t attend the latest SC34 meeting physically in Oslo =
(I corresponded=20
by email on some WG1 issues relating to Schematron and maintenance), but =
the=20
public documents from the meeting have now been released at the <A=20
href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/">SC34</A> website, in =
particular at the=20
<A=20
href=3D"http://lucia.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/itscj/servlets/ScmDoc10?Com_Id=3D34=
">document=20
website</A> (Click on GO for N1000 to N1050.)</P>
<P>One extraordinary document, which I was graciously asked to co-sign, =
can be=20
found on the front page. It is <A=20
href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/open/sc34_openletter_oslo.htm">A=
n open=20
letter from SC 34 participants in the Oslo plenary, April 2008</A> and =
it makes=20
a point so obvious it should not have to be made (but so important we =
all need=20
to remind ourselves of it: it is just as wrong-headed to think that this =
is=20
something =E2=80=9Cthey=E2=80=9D do but =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=9D could not, =
as it is to think that =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=9D are=20
justified in doing it just because =E2=80=9Cthey=E2=80=9D did it first =
or more.) </P>
<P>SC34 is the ISO/IEC JTC1 steering committee on Document Description =
and=20
Processing Languages. It historically grew out of the technical and =
reference=20
publishing industry, as the group that developed SGML in the mid 1980s. =
In the=20
mid-1990s many of us moved over to working through W3C to re-brand, =
re-jig and=20
re-launch SGML under the name of XML, which has been moderately =
successful. SC34=20
has continued on in several main efforts: WG1 looks after schemas and =
markup=20
(ISO/OASIS RELAX NG, ISO Schematron, etc) and recently handed over =
maintenance=20
of the ISO standard public entity sets to the W3C MathML working group; =
WG2=20
looks after fonts and presentation issues, with a particularly strong =
Japanese=20
industrial input, and is involved in the continuing development and =
maintenance=20
of ISO Open Type (which people know as TrueType); WG3 looks after Topic =
Maps,=20
which are a level above RDF in the semantic food chain.</P>
<P>An SC34 meeting typically has an opening general <I>plenary</I> =
(which means=20
everyone is supposed to attend, though only NB delegations get to vote), =
then=20
breaks out into various working groups, then have a final general =
plenary on the=20
last day, which passes various <I>resolutions</I> that are the real =
outcomes of=20
the meeting. (It seems they are giving up the opening plenary, which =
will allow=20
more flexibility for Working Group scheduling: because SC34 has a strong =
rule=20
that agendas and important issues need to be submitted well before the =
meetings,=20
in order for full participation by NBs who might have additional =
language or=20
culture burdens with Western-style disputational meetings and argy =
bargy.) Often=20
the SC34 and WG meetings piggyback on some XML-related conference, to =
help each=20
other=E2=80=99s attendences and because it can make room bookings =
easier. </P>
<P>The <A =
href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/open/1025.htm">Resolutions</A>=20
of the meeting include a few items of interest, but I suppose readers =
will be=20
most interested in the IS29500 (OOXML) resolutions, so here is a =
summary:</P>
<UL>
  <LI>SC 34 will create three distinct working groups to handle=20
  maintenance/liaison/development of IS 26300 (ODF), IS 29500 (OOXML), =
and=20
  interoperability/convergence between document standards. These should =
be=20
  operational at the next SC34 meeting, in Korea in October. <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/open/1018.pdf">Ecma TC45</A> =
has been=20
  invited to participate, with SC34 being the focus of activity rather =
than=20
  Ecma. I anticipate that new feature requests (rather than defect =
fixes) will=20
  need to be dealt with through the interoperabilty Working Group: it =
will be a=20
  very interesting group with a lot of interest from governments in =
particular.=20
  <LI>For the short-term, two <I>ad hoc</I> groups have been set up. =
One,=20
  convened by Japan=E2=80=99s Murata-san will deal with immediate =
collection of comments=20
  and defect reports on IS 29500, to make sure that all the un-resolved, =

  under-resolved and new issues that are reported by NBs get dealt with =
by the=20
  most effective route at the time (which I presume means Ecma TC45 in =
the next=20
  few months, then SC34 after the new Working Groups have been =
established.=20
  <LI>Related to this working group, SC34 is explicitly encouraging =
National=20
  Bodies and liaison groups to submit their editorial and technical =
defect=20
  reports, so that they can get dealt with sooner rather than later. I =
have been=20
  told there have already been some forwarded on to the Editor (who will =
be=20
  discussing them with Ecma TC45, I presume.) Phrases such as =
=E2=80=9Cefficient and=20
  timely process=E2=80=9D are actually quite significant, because they =
indicate that=20
  SC34 has performance requirements which must be met (by itself, by the =
editor,=20
  by participants like Ecma) and that some kind of wishy-washy =
time-dragging=20
  maintenance effort will not be acceptable: all withing the constraint =
that=20
  work will only progress when there are people actually doing it: =
National=20
  Bodies and individuals who are interested or stakeholders or =
beneficiaries of=20
  a standard need to get involved with actual resources. Some of the =
newer=20
  P-members like South Africa seem to be doing exactly the right thing =
here,=20
  getting involved. And the more technical expertise, the better. =
(People need=20
  to remember that for ISO openness is more about being open to =
participate=20
  rather than being open to armchair criticism.)=20
  <LI>The other new Working Group, convened by UK=E2=80=99s Alex Brown, =
will look at the=20
  formalities and terms of references for the new Working Groups. (At =
the last=20
  SC34 meeting in Kyoto late last year, SC34 declined to set up groups =
until IS=20
  29500 had been accepted.) Interestingly, in terms of reference for =
this ad hoc=20
  group include the need for the maintenance process to have =
transparency, the=20
  desirability that there should not be separate versions of Ecma and =
ISO OOXML=20
  (of interest to the future of ISO ODF?), and that Fast-track and PAS=20
  mechanisms should not play any part in the maintenance.=20
  <LI>Along these lines, SC34 also has a rather odd reference to =
increasing its=20
  participation in the JTC1 working group on Directives. I presume this =
is a=20
  concrete sign of the strong desire to work on limiting or reform the =
various=20
  fast-track procedures. I would expect that more National Bodies will =
take the=20
  line =E2=80=9CWe will not vote for any Fast-tracked or PAS drafts to =
SC34=E2=80=B3 and instead=20
  submitters will use the <I>accelerated process</I> instead: this gives =
one=20
  extra stage of committee review by SC34: a fraction slower but =
certainly=20
  better for preventing induced panic attacks, if you know what I mean, =
and=20
  improving quality. (The JTC1 group is set to discuss problems with =
Fast-track=20
  and PAS in its July 2008 meeting: the ISO and JTC1 Directives which =
direct=20
  procedures at SC34 are under frequent revision.)=20
  <LI>Another resolution of interest, is Resolution 1, which in part =
says <I>SC=20
  34 resolves that accessibility considerations will be taken fully into =
account=20
  in current and future projects and urges its members to review the =
work of=20
  JTC1 SWG-A (especially PDTR 29138), W3C WAI and others, and to play an =
active=20
  part in the implementation and further development of accessibility=20
  guidelines</I>. One of the things that came out of the ODF and OOXML =
reviews=20
  was that accessibility is (with internationalization) undoubtedly a=20
  bottom-line issue, indeed a legitimate showstopper: Canada and New =
Zealand=20
  were admirably strong on this at the OOXML BRM for example, and both =
IS 26300=20
  and IS 29500 had some good improvements for accessibility during the =
initial=20
  adoption process. But for living technologies, the acceptance of a =
standard=20
  needs to be the beginning, not the end. So this resolution gives =
practical=20
  ways to approach it: in particular the need for SC34 delegations to =
have=20
  appropriate expertise in accessibility. </LI></UL>
<P>It didn=E2=80=99t seem a bad meeting. I don=E2=80=99t have =
information, but I do hope the=20
P-countries which only have interest in ODF and OOXML make the =
appropriate=20
arrangements with SC34 and JTC1 to register default abstain votes on =
WG1, WG2=20
and WG3 ballots. It is really important. </P>
<P>My own hope is that many of the participants on the DIS 29500 who =
came up to=20
speed in the technical and standards issues of their expertise, will =
channel=20
their enthusiasm into places where it can actually make a difference: =
get=20
involved in your local standards National Body SC34 mirror committee =
long term,=20
get involved in OASIS ODF and OpenFormula, get involved in W3C, get =
involved in=20
Ecma TC45, get involved in SC 34. Lobby for more openness at all levels. =
Keep=20
the pressure on both sides (err, on *all* sides!), so that the =
differentiators=20
between ODF and OOXML become clearer and gratuitous differences get =
sanded down,=20
because it is this competitive pressure that is forcing improvements on =
both=20
sides, not the ISO stamp per se! <B>No pressure without participation; =
no=20
participation without pressure!</B></P>
<HR>

<P>[UPDATE] For a real blog from someone who attended, see Alex =
Brown=E2=80=99s <A=20
href=3D"http://adjb.net/index.php?entry=3Dentry080409-221633">ISO =
committee takes=20
full control of OOXML</A>.</P>
<P>I missed putting in a reference to the German standard body =
DIN=E2=80=99s <A=20
href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/open/1026.pdf">update</A> on =
its working=20
group on ODF/OOXML translation, which is one of the major pieces of =
intelligence=20
needed before any serious co-evolution/convergence/harmonization work =
can occur.=20
(It is not in the report, but I believe there is some idea that DIN =
should=20
present its information as an ISO Topic Map, to allow better =
programmatic=20
navigation and use of the mappings, and to make it easier to add =
mappings to=20
further languages (W3C? UOF? MIF? binaries?) if needed=E2=80=A6 ) </P>
